# Code Style — TypeScript

- Use TypeScript strict mode — no implicit any
- Prefer named exports over default exports (except tool components)
- Use const for all declarations unless mutation is required
- File names: PascalCase for components, camelCase for utilities
- Always add JSDoc comments to exported functions and types

# Code Style — Rust

- All public functions must have doc comments (///)
- Use thiserror for error types — never panic! in library code
- Derive Debug, Clone, Serialize, Deserialize on all public structs

## Return type convention for instrument-core
Most tool functions return a plain Output struct (NOT Result) with an embedded
`error: Option<String>` field. This lets the frontend always receive a structured
response and handle errors in the UI.

```rust
// ✅ Standard pattern — infallible at the type level, error embedded in output
pub fn process(input: Base64Input) -> Base64Output {
    Base64Output { value: ..., error: None }
}

// ✅ Acceptable — when the operation is genuinely fallible at the command level
pub fn process(input: JsonFormatInput) -> Result<JsonFormatOutput, String> { ... }
```

Always follow the pattern of the nearest similar existing tool.
Do not introduce `Result` where the existing pattern uses `Output { error: Option<String> }`.

# Serialisation

- Use serde for all Rust/TypeScript data exchange
- All Tauri commands receive and return named structs — not primitives
- Use `#[serde(rename_all = "camelCase")]` on all structs exchanged with the frontend

# When generating code

- Follow the pattern in the nearest similar existing file
- Add the function to the relevant module export
- Include the test alongside the implementation
- Update the registry if adding a new tool
